-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Cal Bank, East African Portland, Unity Bank Move
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k   a n d   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 2010-10-06T17:07:05Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-06/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-cal-bank-east-african-portland-unity-bank-move.html
The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index  fell for the first day in six, retreating 0.9 percent to
24,035.92 by the 1 p.m. close in Lagos, according to the
bourse’s website.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  rose for a third day, adding 0.4
percent to 1,781.02 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis.
Kenya’s  All-Share Index  was unchanged at 81.86 by the 3 p.m.
close in Nairobi. Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  advanced
for the third day, gaining 1.5 percent to close at 817.09 by 4
p.m. in Windhoek. The  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  rose
for the second day, adding 0.2 percent to 6,822.64 by the close
at 1 p.m. in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Cal Bank Ltd.  (CAL GN), a Ghanaian lender, rose to the
highest in two weeks rallying 1 pesewa, or 3.5 percent, to 30
pesewas. Some investors are speculating that profit rose in the
fiscal third quarter, to be released in two weeks’ time,
Emmanuel Tsigbey, a trader with the Ghanaian unit of Renaissance
Capital, said in an interview from Accra. “We foresee a profit
rise of between 30 and 40 percent for Cal this third quarter
over the same quarter last year.”  East African Portland Cement Ltd.  (EAPC KN), Kenya’s
second-biggest maker of the building material, fell 4 shillings,
or 3.5 percent, to 112 shillings, the lowest since May 7. The
company posted a loss of 292.4 million shillings ($3.6 million)
in the year through June, compared with a year-earlier profit of
1.83 billion shillings, it said today.  Unity Bank Plc  (UNITYBNK NL), one of the 10 Nigerian
lenders bailed out by the central bank last year after a debt
crisis, rose to its highest since Sept. 27 climbing 3 kobo, or
4.3 percent, to 73 kobo.  The lender held a rights offer to meet a Central Bank of
Nigeria “regulatory capital requirement” of 25 billion naira
($165 million), Mohammed Abdullahi, spokesman for the Abuja-
based regulator, said in an e-mailed statement yesterday.  To contact the reporters on this story:
